---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'AXA Global in Mexico', level: 2 },
  { id: 'eu-regulation', text: 'EU Insurer in Mexico', level: 2 },
  { id: 'mexico-network', text: 'Network Coverage in Mexico', level: 2 },
  { id: 'plans-and-pricing', text: 'Plans and Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'vs-us-insurers', text: 'vs US Insurers (Aetna, GeoBlue)', level: 2 },
  { id: 'imss-combo', text: 'IMSS + AXA Strategy', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-its-for', text: 'Who Should Choose AXA', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Health Insurance in Mexico', href: '/countries/mexico/insurance' },
  { title: 'AXA Global Review', href: '/providers/axa-global' },
  { title: 'AXA vs Allianz', href: '/compare/axa-global-vs-allianz-care' },
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'plan', header: 'Plan' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage' },
  { key: 'mexicoPrice', header: 'Mexico (Age 35)' },
  { key: 'usOption', header: 'US Coverage' },
];

const planRows = [
  { plan: 'Essential', coverage: 'Inpatient + Emergency', mexicoPrice: '$95-125/mo', usOption: '+40-50%' },
  { plan: 'Comfort', coverage: 'Essential + Outpatient', mexicoPrice: '$145-190/mo', usOption: '+40-50%' },
  { plan: 'Excellence', coverage: 'Comprehensive', mexicoPrice: '$200-270/mo', usOption: '+40-50%' },
  { plan: 'Exclusive', coverage: 'Unlimited', mexicoPrice: '$320-420/mo', usOption: '+40-50%' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'factor', header: 'Factor' },
  { key: 'axa', header: 'AXA Global' },
  { key: 'usInsurers', header: 'Aetna/GeoBlue' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { factor: 'Monthly Cost (Age 35, no US)', axa: '$145-190', usInsurers: '$175-280' },
  { factor: 'Monthly Cost (with US)', axa: '$200-280', usInsurers: '$175-280 (included)' },
  { factor: 'Regulation', axa: 'EU (Solvency II)', usInsurers: 'US' },
  { factor: 'Currency', axa: 'EUR or USD', usInsurers: 'USD' },
  { factor: 'Network in Mexico', axa: 'Good', usInsurers: 'Good' },
  { factor: 'US Network', axa: 'Optional add-on', usInsurers: 'Full integrated' },
  { factor: 'Best For', axa: 'EU expats, non-Americans', usInsurers: 'US expats' },
];

const hospitalColumns = [
  { key: 'city', header: 'City' },
  { key: 'hospitals', header: 'Network Hospitals' },
  { key: 'directBilling', header: 'Direct Billing' },
];

const hospitalRows = [
  { city: 'Mexico City', hospitals: 'Hospital ABC, Médica Sur, Hospital Ángeles', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Guadalajara', hospitals: 'Hospital San Javier, Hospital Country 2000', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Monterrey', hospitals: 'Christus Muguerza, Hospital San José', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Puerto Vallarta', hospitals: 'Hospital CMQ, Hospiten', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Cancún', hospitals: 'Hospiten Cancún, Galenia Hospital', directBilling: true },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="AXA Global Health Insurance in Mexico"
  description="Guide to using AXA Global in Mexico. EU-regulated insurer for European expats and those who don't need US coverage. Network, pricing, and comparisons."
  headline="AXA Global Health Insurance in Mexico"
  subheadline="European insurance giant with worldwide coverage. Lower premiums when you don't need US coverage—ideal for EU expats in Mexico."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/mexico-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get an AXA Mexico Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/axa-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">AXA Global in Mexico</h2>
  <p>
    AXA Global Healthcare is one of the world's largest international health insurers. For expats in Mexico who don't need US coverage, AXA offers competitive pricing—15-25% less than US-focused insurers like Aetna or GeoBlue that bundle US networks into the price.
  </p>
  <p>
    Mexico doesn't require health insurance for residency visas, so AXA's EU regulatory status (useful for European visas) matters less here. What matters is solid worldwide coverage, a good Mexican network, and cost-effective premiums—which AXA delivers.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">1.6M+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Providers worldwide</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">EU</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Regulated (Solvency II)</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€/$</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Currency flexibility</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Get a Mexico-Specific Quote"
    description="See what AXA Global costs with or without US coverage."
    buttonText="Get Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/axa-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="eu-regulation">EU Insurer in Mexico</h2>
  <p>
    AXA is headquartered in Paris and regulated under EU Solvency II rules. What does this mean for expats in Mexico?
  </p>

  <h3>Benefits of EU Regulation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Consumer protections:</strong> EU Solvency II requirements ensure financial stability</li>
    <li><strong>GDPR compliance:</strong> Strong data protection</li>
    <li><strong>Dispute resolution:</strong> EU consumer protection mechanisms</li>
    <li><strong>European connections:</strong> If you later move to Europe, AXA is already established</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Less Relevant in Mexico</h3>
  <p>
    Unlike European countries, Mexico doesn't require insurance for residency visas—so AXA's EU credibility doesn't help with visa applications. The main practical benefits are pricing and portability:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No US subsidy:</strong> AXA's excluding-USA plans don't subsidize US networks</li>
    <li><strong>Euro option:</strong> Bill in EUR if you have euro income</li>
    <li><strong>EU portability:</strong> If you move to Europe later, coverage continues</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="mexico-network">Network Coverage in Mexico</h2>
  <p>
    AXA has a solid network in Mexico, with direct billing at major private hospitals.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={hospitalColumns} rows={hospitalRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Coverage by Region</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mexico City:</strong> Excellent coverage at top hospitals (ABC, Médica Sur, Ángeles)</li>
    <li><strong>Guadalajara:</strong> Good network coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Monterrey:</strong> Strong presence at major hospitals</li>
    <li><strong>Beach destinations:</strong> Coverage in Puerto Vallarta, Cancún, Los Cabos</li>
    <li><strong>Smaller cities:</strong> Use any provider and claim reimbursement</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Finding Providers</h3>
  <p>
    Use AXA's MyHealth portal or app to find:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Direct-billing hospitals</li>
    <li>English or Spanish-speaking doctors</li>
    <li>Specialists in your area</li>
    <li>Urgent care facilities</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Out-of-Network Care</h3>
  <p>
    You can use any licensed provider in Mexico. Pay upfront and submit for reimbursement—Mexican facturas (receipts) are accepted without translation. AXA reimburses at usual, customary, and reasonable (UCR) rates.
  </p>

  <h2 id="plans-and-pricing">Plans and Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    AXA offers four tiers. Excluding-USA plans are 15-25% cheaper than US-inclusive options.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <em>Prices for worldwide coverage excluding USA. Add 40-50% for US coverage.</em>
  </p>

  <h3>Plan Recommendations for Mexico</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Essential:</strong> Hospital-only. Budget option if you're healthy and want catastrophic coverage plus IMSS for routine care.</li>
    <li><strong>Comfort:</strong> Most practical for Mexico. Includes outpatient, dental basics. Good balance.</li>
    <li><strong>Excellence:</strong> Comprehensive with mental health parity. Good for families or ongoing health needs.</li>
    <li><strong>Exclusive:</strong> Unlimited coverage. Maximum protection available.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Deductible Strategy</h3>
  <p>
    Mexican healthcare is affordable. Consider:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Doctor visit: $30-60</li>
    <li>Specialist: $50-100</li>
    <li>Lab work: $20-50</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A €1,000-2,500 deductible significantly reduces premiums. Pay routine care out of pocket and use AXA for hospitals and major expenses.
  </p>

  <h3>Currency Options</h3>
  <p>
    AXA offers euro or USD billing. For expats with euro income or European ties, euro billing avoids currency conversion costs.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Lower Premiums Without US Coverage"
    description="If you don't need US coverage, AXA offers competitive pricing."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/axa-global"
  />

  <h2 id="vs-us-insurers">vs US Insurers (Aetna, GeoBlue)</h2>
  <p>
    How does AXA compare to US-focused insurers?
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Key Differences</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>US coverage:</strong> Aetna and GeoBlue include full US network access in their base price. AXA's US coverage is an optional add-on that costs 40-50% more. If you don't need US coverage, AXA is cheaper. If you do, Aetna/GeoBlue are better value.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for Americans:</strong> US expats who visit family or might need US specialists should choose Aetna or GeoBlue—US coverage is integrated and optimized.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for Europeans/others:</strong> Non-American expats who don't need US coverage get better value from AXA's excluding-USA plans.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">US Expat Note</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      If you're American and might visit the US (for family, specialists, or emergencies), consider <a href="/countries/mexico/insurance/aetna-international" class="underline">Aetna</a> or <a href="/countries/mexico/insurance/geoblue" class="underline">GeoBlue</a> instead. Their integrated US coverage is optimized for Americans and typically better value than adding US coverage to AXA.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="imss-combo">IMSS + AXA Strategy</h2>
  <p>
    Like other international insurers, AXA works well combined with IMSS:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">The Combination Approach</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
      <li><strong>IMSS ($500/year):</strong> Routine care, prescriptions, basic backup</li>
      <li><strong>AXA Essential ($95/mo):</strong> Private hospitals, worldwide travel, emergencies</li>
      <li><strong>Total: ~$225/month</strong> for comprehensive international coverage without US</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>When to Use Each</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>IMSS:</strong> Routine care, generic medications, basic checkups</li>
    <li><strong>AXA:</strong> Private hospitals, English-speaking doctors, travel coverage, emergencies</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    IMSS (~$40/month for under-60s) is affordable backup for routine care, freeing AXA for major medical.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Should Choose AXA</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Ideal For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>European expats in Mexico</li>
        <li>Non-Americans who don't need US coverage</li>
        <li>Those who might move to Europe later</li>
        <li>French or Spanish speakers</li>
        <li>Expats wanting euro billing</li>
        <li>Budget-conscious who don't visit the US</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Consider Alternatives</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>US expats (Aetna/GeoBlue better for US access)</li>
        <li>Budget-focused (IMSS or SafetyWing cheaper)</li>
        <li>Those wanting largest Mexican network</li>
        <li>Permanent Mexico residents</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is AXA good for Americans in Mexico?</h3>
  <p>
    AXA works for Americans, but if you visit the US at all, Aetna or GeoBlue are better value—they include full US network access in the base price. If you're American but never plan to receive care in the US, AXA's excluding-USA plans are cheaper.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I add US coverage to AXA later?</h3>
  <p>
    You can upgrade your coverage area at renewal. Adding US coverage increases premiums by approximately 40-50%. If you anticipate needing US coverage eventually, starting with a US-inclusive insurer may be simpler.
  </p>

  <h3>Does AXA cover Mexican public hospitals?</h3>
  <p>
    AXA is private insurance for private healthcare. Emergency care at public hospitals may be reimbursed. For routine public healthcare, enroll in IMSS separately.
  </p>

  <h3>What languages does AXA support?</h3>
  <p>
    24/7 support in English and French. Spanish support during business hours. Claims in Spanish accepted without translation.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I use AXA and IMSS together?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. IMSS (~$500/year) handles routine care, AXA handles private hospitals, worldwide travel, and major medical. It's a cost-effective combination.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for International Coverage?"
    description="Get a personalized AXA Global quote for Mexico."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/axa-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Network availability, pricing, and coverage terms change. We are not insurance brokers. Verify all information with AXA Global before making decisions.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
